WEBVTT

00:58.640 --> 01:00.360
-Hello.
-Hello, everybody!

01:00.400 --> 01:02.400
Thank you so much.

01:04.200 --> 01:06.680
-Thank you!
-Thank you.

01:06.720 --> 01:08.080
JEREMY:
Greetings!

01:08.120 --> 01:10.480
Thank you, thank you,
thank you.

01:12.440 --> 01:15.000
Thank you, everybody.
Thank you.

01:16.800 --> 01:18.360
And welcome,
and thank you all

01:18.400 --> 01:22.080
for braving these treacherous
conditions to get here.

01:22.120 --> 01:25.080
-It took me nearly
nine minutes this morning.

01:25.120 --> 01:27.240
His slippers got all soggy
on the way.

01:27.280 --> 01:29.080
I nearly fell over once,
but I made it.

01:29.120 --> 01:30.200
Don't worry,

01:30.240 --> 01:32.520
because we have an incredible
reward for you all.

01:32.560 --> 01:35.720
Because, in this
action-packed show...

01:37.080 --> 01:40.720
..James wears a red anorak...

01:40.760 --> 01:43.440
..Richard looks at a pipe
of some sort...

01:44.640 --> 01:47.640
..and I make a cup of tea.

01:51.520 --> 01:54.560
It is non-stop action.

01:54.600 --> 01:59.040
Non-stop. But...
but we begin with mankind.

01:59.080 --> 02:01.440
-Wow! Big start!
-It is a big start.

02:01.480 --> 02:03.280
You see, the thing is,
as a species,

02:03.320 --> 02:05.080
we are very pleased
with ourselves,

02:05.120 --> 02:07.680
because we have
the Porsche 918

02:07.720 --> 02:08.960
and the Ferrari TheFerrari:

02:09.000 --> 02:13.200
cars that can travel at
212mph, an incredible speed.

02:13.240 --> 02:15.800
Whereas cows and ants and...

02:15.840 --> 02:19.200
-Well, think about it, OK.

02:19.240 --> 02:21.240
A cow is exactly the same now

02:21.280 --> 02:22.840
as it was
a million years ago.

02:22.880 --> 02:24.720
Well, maybe a bit more
delicious now,

02:24.760 --> 02:25.920
but basically the same.

02:25.960 --> 02:28.480
It still stands around
all day long

02:28.520 --> 02:29.920
in a field eating grass.

02:29.960 --> 02:32.440
Whereas we think
that we've improved.

02:32.480 --> 02:34.360
But have we?

02:34.400 --> 02:35.480
-Yes.
-Yeah, we have.

02:35.520 --> 02:36.880
Well, now, you say that,

02:36.920 --> 02:40.320
but we were travelling
at way more than 212mph

02:40.360 --> 02:43.560
in our cars 25 years ago.

02:54.440 --> 02:57.320
JEREMY: This is
the Jaguar XJ220.

03:01.040 --> 03:06.120
And with a top speed
of 217mph,

03:06.160 --> 03:08.400
it was the fastest car
in the world.

03:10.240 --> 03:12.680
For about five minutes.

03:12.720 --> 03:14.560
And then this came along.

03:18.080 --> 03:23.720
The 218mph
Bugatti EB 110 Super Sport.

03:31.880 --> 03:34.960
Both these cars
were conceived in the '80s,

03:35.000 --> 03:36.920
when Gordon Gekko
was running amok,

03:36.960 --> 03:39.760
and the world
was awash with money.

03:41.240 --> 03:44.400
But by the time they went
on sale in the early '90s...

03:44.440 --> 03:46.400
An incredible day
on Wall Street.

03:46.440 --> 03:48.440
The market has fallen
over 400 points.

03:48.480 --> 03:50.880
JEREMY: ...the stock market
had crashed.

03:50.920 --> 03:52.880
There's only one word to
describe what's happening,

03:52.920 --> 03:54.440
and that is "panic".

03:54.480 --> 03:57.880
JEREMY: So, the only people
who might have bought them

03:57.920 --> 04:00.800
were too busy
hurling themselves
out of their office windows

04:00.840 --> 04:02.080
on Wall Street.

04:03.600 --> 04:07.960
So, these cars,
they came, they conquered,

04:08.000 --> 04:09.840
and no-one noticed.

04:11.200 --> 04:14.520
Today, though,
25 years later,

04:14.560 --> 04:17.960
there are only three cars
in current production

04:18.000 --> 04:19.880
that are faster than this.

04:21.120 --> 04:23.840
However, while there is
a lot of performance,

04:23.880 --> 04:26.880
the way it's delivered is...
quite old-fashioned.

04:26.920 --> 04:29.040
You put your foot down,
and then you wait

04:29.080 --> 04:31.080
while the turbo-chargers
spool up.

04:32.760 --> 04:35.120
It takes quite a while,
cos there are four of them.

04:41.200 --> 04:42.760
Talk among yourselves.

04:42.800 --> 04:46.640
However, when the 3.5l V12

04:46.680 --> 04:49.080
is finally getting
all the food it needs...

04:50.440 --> 04:52.160
Oh, God!

04:52.200 --> 04:53.920
..all hell breaks loose.

04:58.240 --> 04:59.320
Oh!

05:03.320 --> 05:04.440
Through the corner.

05:06.680 --> 05:07.840
Mild terror.

05:10.200 --> 05:12.920
The speed is hilarious!

05:15.520 --> 05:16.960
And terrifying.

05:19.240 --> 05:20.720
That's probably why
they fitted it

05:20.760 --> 05:24.000
with this plastic sheeting
rather than carpets,

05:24.040 --> 05:27.600
because they knew that one
day you would soil yourself.

05:30.560 --> 05:32.240
You did have to be good

05:32.280 --> 05:33.960
to get the best
out of this thing.

05:35.080 --> 05:37.400
Which brings me on to
Michael Schumacher.

05:37.440 --> 05:41.680
He could have had any car
he wanted back in the day,

05:41.720 --> 05:43.280
but he had one of these.

05:44.320 --> 05:45.480
Weirdly, however,

05:45.520 --> 05:47.920
and mainly because
I think it looks better,

05:47.960 --> 05:50.240
I'd have chosen the Jag.

06:01.920 --> 06:06.000
It was supposed to have been
a four-wheel drive V12,

06:06.040 --> 06:09.040
like the Bugatti,

06:09.080 --> 06:11.200
but Jaguar found that
much too complicated.

06:11.240 --> 06:13.880
So, they gave it
the turbo-charged V6

06:13.920 --> 06:15.440
from a Metro rally car,

06:15.480 --> 06:19.880
rear-wheel drive,
the rear lights
from a Rover 200,

06:19.920 --> 06:22.680
and then they said,
"That'll do,"

06:22.720 --> 06:24.880
and went to the pub.

06:29.400 --> 06:33.000
So, does that mean the Jag
is embarrassed by the Bugatti

06:33.040 --> 06:34.800
in a drag race?

06:39.280 --> 06:40.640
Right, before we do this,

06:40.680 --> 06:44.240
I have to tape
the cassette player in place,

06:44.280 --> 06:48.080
because the last time I did
a full-bore standing start

06:48.120 --> 06:49.960
in an XJ220,

06:50.000 --> 06:52.200
the acceleration
was so vivid,

06:52.240 --> 06:55.520
the stereo shot out
of its slot in the dashboard,

06:55.560 --> 06:58.760
ricocheted
off the gear lever,

06:58.800 --> 07:01.480
and then speared
into my left plum.

07:01.520 --> 07:03.520
It was very uncomfortable.

07:05.040 --> 07:06.880
Oh, the end's come off.

07:09.360 --> 07:11.760
That's good.
Right, window up.

07:27.120 --> 07:28.840
Right, let's do this!

07:50.480 --> 07:51.800
Don't know when
to change gear,

07:51.840 --> 07:53.680
because the rev counter's
broken.

07:58.960 --> 08:00.360
This is close.

08:03.280 --> 08:05.120
Oh, my word! Ha!

08:09.280 --> 08:12.040
Score one for the Jag!

08:13.040 --> 08:16.120
Whoa! That was some speed!

08:17.720 --> 08:19.240
After a quarter of a mile,

08:19.280 --> 08:24.280
the badly-made Jag
was doing 135mph,

08:24.320 --> 08:28.320
and a modern day Lamborghini
Huracan couldn't do that.

08:28.360 --> 08:33.080
Which proves that in the last
25 years, we've come nowhere.

08:34.240 --> 08:35.360
Except, we have.

08:36.960 --> 08:39.400
You see, back in '92 and '93,

08:39.440 --> 08:42.160
there was no Wi-Fi,
there was no PlayStation,

08:42.200 --> 08:44.640
DVD hadn't been invented,

08:44.680 --> 08:47.520
Justin Bieber
hadn't been born.

08:47.560 --> 08:49.920
There was no Google,
Amazon was a river.

08:49.960 --> 08:51.840
There was no
internet pornography.

08:51.880 --> 08:53.360
Well, that's probably
a good thing,

08:53.400 --> 08:54.880
cos there was no Viagra,
either.

08:54.920 --> 08:57.640
The early '90s
were the dark ages,

08:57.680 --> 09:01.360
and when you drive
these cars, it shows.

09:10.960 --> 09:13.720
In here,
there's no power-steering.

09:14.880 --> 09:16.000
No air conditioning.

09:17.240 --> 09:18.600
No anti-lock brakes.

09:20.800 --> 09:24.080
And obviously,
no driver aids of any kind.

09:29.920 --> 09:34.360
Got a 525bhp engine
back there.

09:38.480 --> 09:39.600
Ooh, shi...

09:41.520 --> 09:45.320
Being fed by a turbo-charger
the size of a wheelie bin.

09:48.400 --> 09:52.880
And all there is in here
to tame it is me!

10:00.360 --> 10:01.560
Ah!

10:03.000 --> 10:04.120
Oh!

10:09.600 --> 10:11.680
After a couple of laps
in this thing,

10:11.720 --> 10:13.560
you really are aching.

10:13.600 --> 10:15.040
And sweating.

10:15.080 --> 10:17.320
And you're frightened.
You really are.

10:17.360 --> 10:20.920
Cos this is not a car that's
just gonna forgive you.

10:20.960 --> 10:24.440
If you overdo it,
you're gonna hit a tree,

10:24.480 --> 10:26.240
and that's just an end of it.

10:39.040 --> 10:40.760
So, there we are.

10:43.120 --> 10:45.160
A modern supercar
may be no faster

10:45.200 --> 10:47.720
than these monsters
from the past,

10:47.760 --> 10:51.640
but a modern supercar
makes the speed fun and easy,

10:51.680 --> 10:57.240
not terrifying
and bathed in an unholy mix
of sweat and faeces.

11:04.960 --> 11:06.320
Well done.

11:07.320 --> 11:08.400
Covered it all there.

11:09.560 --> 11:10.680
No, seriously, well done,

11:10.720 --> 11:12.600
because nobody's ever
finished a road test

11:12.640 --> 11:14.480
with the word "faeces"
before.

11:14.520 --> 11:15.720
No, that was a first.

11:15.760 --> 11:16.880
But I'm just thinking,

11:16.920 --> 11:19.320
it isn't just supercars
that are getting slower,

11:19.360 --> 11:21.320
because you remember
the Lotus Sunbeam?

11:21.360 --> 11:24.160
-Yeah.

11:24.200 --> 11:26.920
That did 0-60 in 6.6 seconds,

11:26.960 --> 11:28.240
and there aren't many
hot hatches

11:28.280 --> 11:29.920
that would keep up with that,
even today.

11:29.960 --> 11:32.200
And then you've got trains.
The Mallard, the steam train,

11:32.240 --> 11:33.640
is quicker
than most electric trains.

11:33.680 --> 11:37.560
SR-71 Blackbird, nothing
in the skies as fast as that.

11:37.600 --> 11:38.880
I suppose,
if you think about it,
we used to be able

11:38.920 --> 11:41.000
to get across the Atlantic
in three hours,

11:41.040 --> 11:42.800
-and now it takes us seven.
-Exactly.

11:42.840 --> 11:45.760
And now we must put some
numbers on our argument

11:45.800 --> 11:49.480
by sending the Bugatti
round the Eboladrome.

11:51.400 --> 11:53.040
Come on, old-timer!

11:55.000 --> 11:57.080
JEREMY: And she's off.

11:57.120 --> 11:58.200
A smooth start.

11:58.240 --> 12:00.600
Four-wheel drive system
maintaining traction

12:00.640 --> 12:03.520
in these wet conditions.

12:03.560 --> 12:06.200
It really is soaking
out there today!

12:06.240 --> 12:09.760
Right, a measured line
through the first curve,

12:09.800 --> 12:12.240
and then carefully
working the throttle

12:12.280 --> 12:14.000
to keep things in check.

12:14.040 --> 12:16.600
Approaching the sweep
down to Your Name Here,

12:16.640 --> 12:18.240
and smoothly done.

12:19.680 --> 12:22.560
Crikey! Managing to get
the tyres squealing,

12:22.600 --> 12:24.760
even on this damp section.

12:24.800 --> 12:26.920
And then winding up
the little V12

12:26.960 --> 12:30.200
to fire it back
onto the Isn't.

12:30.240 --> 12:32.880
Single wiper
batting away the drizzle,

12:32.920 --> 12:35.040
as she hustles it
towards the braking zone

12:35.080 --> 12:38.040
for the tricky
Old Lady's House complex.

12:38.080 --> 12:40.080
How will it get on here?

12:40.120 --> 12:41.800
Very neat.

12:41.840 --> 12:44.160
Very controlled.

12:44.200 --> 12:47.760
And now back on the gas
for the run to Substation.

12:47.800 --> 12:49.640
And you can hear the fizz

12:49.680 --> 12:52.680
from those four
furiously spinning turbos.

12:52.720 --> 12:55.000
Keeping it together there
nicely.

12:55.040 --> 12:56.200
Field Of Sheep to go.

12:56.240 --> 12:58.520
Glides through there,
and across the line.

13:04.640 --> 13:07.680
So, let's see where
it goes on the board.

13:07.720 --> 13:09.360
I'm imagining pretty high up.

13:09.400 --> 13:10.560
Oh.

13:11.880 --> 13:13.720
-That's not very fast.
-No, it isn't very fast.

13:13.760 --> 13:16.000
But we put the Jag round,
as well,

13:16.040 --> 13:17.480
and that did it in...

13:17.520 --> 13:19.800
Hang on,
I've got the time here.
Just bear with me.

13:19.840 --> 13:21.840
..one thirty-five one.

13:21.880 --> 13:24.920
JAMES: So...
slower than the Bugatti?

13:24.960 --> 13:26.800
Yes.

13:26.840 --> 13:28.240
Slower, in fact,
than everything

13:28.280 --> 13:30.800
except a small, cheap
Volkswagen hatchback,

13:30.840 --> 13:33.120
which also went round
in the soaking wet.

13:33.160 --> 13:35.600
Yes.

13:35.640 --> 13:37.440
So, contrary to what
you were saying earlier on,

13:37.480 --> 13:39.680
supercars have got
much faster

13:39.720 --> 13:41.600
over the last 25 years.

13:43.440 --> 13:45.280
Yes.

13:45.320 --> 13:46.760
Right! Moving on!

13:46.800 --> 13:48.280
Because now it's time

13:48.320 --> 13:50.600
to order
some doughnuts of debate

13:50.640 --> 13:55.640
from the Chat Café,
on Conversation Street.

14:01.600 --> 14:04.480
-I was terrified.
-Yeah.

14:04.520 --> 14:05.840
Right, good. Now...

14:06.960 --> 14:09.080
-Yes.

14:09.120 --> 14:10.200
The only car, incidentally,

14:10.240 --> 14:13.160
designed on the interior
and the exterior by women.

14:13.200 --> 14:14.280
-It was.

14:14.320 --> 14:17.240
Well, they're dropping it,
and replacing it with this.

14:17.280 --> 14:20.080
This has been designed
by a man, so...

14:20.120 --> 14:23.240
Mm-hm. And where are you
going with this one, Jeremy?

14:23.280 --> 14:27.520
So, it won't be able
to take its jumper off

14:27.560 --> 14:29.360
by folding its arms.

14:31.760 --> 14:34.760
Men can't take their jumpers
off like women do,

14:34.800 --> 14:37.360
-crossing their arms.
-I can do that!

14:37.400 --> 14:40.320
-You're not a man.
-Oh, right.

14:40.360 --> 14:41.560
I take my jumper...

14:41.600 --> 14:43.480
That's how you take
a jumper off, like that.

14:43.520 --> 14:45.000
How do you know?

14:45.040 --> 14:47.280
You just wait for the
paramedics to come along,

14:47.320 --> 14:49.160
cut it off
after your accident.

14:49.200 --> 14:51.480
Yes, but that's how
you take a jumper off.

14:51.520 --> 14:53.880
-I don't know
what you're talking about.
-Take your jumper off.

14:53.920 --> 14:56.920
Just take your jumper off.
Watch this.
How does he take it off?

14:56.960 --> 14:58.360
Er, like this.

14:58.400 --> 14:59.800
JEREMY: There, you see?
Like a man.

14:59.840 --> 15:01.320
Are there any women
wanna take...

15:01.360 --> 15:03.840
Oh, no, we can't do that.

15:03.880 --> 15:06.200
Seriously, women, do you know
what I'm on about?

15:06.240 --> 15:07.440
WOMEN: Yes.

15:07.480 --> 15:08.560
Women cross...

15:08.600 --> 15:11.200
If I tried to do that,
I'd dislocate my shoulder!

15:11.240 --> 15:13.440
Thank you for that nonsense,
Jeremy.

15:13.480 --> 15:16.480
Can we maybe get back to
the BMW now, which is a car?

15:16.520 --> 15:17.800
Yes, it is.
Now, I have to say,

15:17.840 --> 15:19.960
the old one was never
as good to drive

15:20.000 --> 15:21.640
-as it was to look at.
-I know what you mean.

15:21.680 --> 15:23.360
It wasn't. It was sort of
baggy, wasn't it?

15:23.400 --> 15:25.000
Yeah, and there was never
an M version.

15:25.040 --> 15:27.200
You know,
it was all just unexciting.

15:27.240 --> 15:28.920
But I'm hoping this new one

15:28.960 --> 15:30.640
is as good to drive
as it looks,

15:30.680 --> 15:32.120
and it does look very good,

15:32.160 --> 15:34.640
-even though it will struggle
with its jumper.
-Yeah, whatever.

15:34.680 --> 15:37.280
Anyway, if I was looking
for a new BMW Z4,

15:37.320 --> 15:40.200
actually, I'd have
one of these,

15:40.240 --> 15:41.880
because this is
the new Toyota Supra.

15:41.920 --> 15:43.400
I know, it looks phenomenal!

15:43.440 --> 15:46.000
And that underneath
is basically a Z4.

15:46.040 --> 15:47.960
-Same engine and everything.
-Same chassis.

15:48.000 --> 15:49.640
It is a Z4,
but with that body.

15:49.680 --> 15:51.560
And that body,
I have to say, looks amazing.

15:51.600 --> 15:53.240
And do you know
the most amazing thing is,

15:53.280 --> 15:55.520
they're talking about a price
between 40,000 and 60,000,

15:55.560 --> 15:57.560
which is much less
than it looks like.

15:57.600 --> 16:00.200
RICHARD: See, I think
that is actually filling
a gap in the market.

16:00.240 --> 16:03.200
There is a need right now
for a mid-price sportscar,

16:03.240 --> 16:05.520
because there really
aren't many, if any.

16:05.560 --> 16:07.160
There's the Audi TT RS.

16:07.200 --> 16:09.960
Well, that'll definitely
take its jumper off
like that, won't it?

16:10.000 --> 16:11.720
And then stow it
in the overhead lockers,

16:11.760 --> 16:13.720
tell you where the doors are.

16:13.760 --> 16:15.760
Now, Volkswagen's
US Head of Regulation -

16:15.800 --> 16:18.800
that was his job title -
a guy called Oliver Schmidt.

16:18.840 --> 16:21.520
He's just been done
for his part in Dieselgate.

16:21.560 --> 16:24.480
And they've given him
seven years in jail.

16:24.520 --> 16:26.680
Or, as he would put it,
4.2 years.

16:32.080 --> 16:33.760
And a fine of £400,000,

16:33.800 --> 16:35.920
or whatever that translates
into VW money.

16:35.960 --> 16:38.640
Two hundred
and seventy thousand.

16:38.680 --> 16:42.080
The fascinating thing is,
there was a warrant out
for his arrest in America,

16:42.120 --> 16:43.400
but he was in Germany.

16:43.440 --> 16:45.000
And then, for some reason,

16:45.040 --> 16:48.320
he decided to take his
annual holiday in Florida,

16:48.360 --> 16:49.800
and got arrested
at the airport.

16:49.840 --> 16:52.120
"Oh, nein!"

16:54.240 --> 16:55.520
-Oh, yeah.
-Well, he must be!

16:55.560 --> 16:57.520
He must be!
The only thing I can think of

16:57.560 --> 17:00.920
is that Volkswagen needed
someone to do some jail time

17:00.960 --> 17:03.200
-for what had happened.

17:03.240 --> 17:04.600
No, I reckon
they probably said,

17:04.640 --> 17:06.600
"You are ze employee
of ze month, Mr Schmidt,

17:06.640 --> 17:08.800
and you have won
a fortnight's holiday

17:08.840 --> 17:10.280
in Disney World!"

17:10.320 --> 17:12.680
-"Ah, danke!"
-And off he toddled.

17:12.720 --> 17:15.040
"Oh, no,
they have arrested me!"

17:15.080 --> 17:18.520
That's actually a seven-year
holiday, Mr Schmidt,

17:18.560 --> 17:20.880
and the catering is terrible.

17:20.920 --> 17:22.760
Now, do you remember
the Rimac we had

17:22.800 --> 17:24.200
in programme one
of this season?

17:24.240 --> 17:25.440
-There it is.
JEREMY: Yeah.

17:25.480 --> 17:28.320
RICHARD: Well,
they've announced there is
a new one coming out.

17:28.360 --> 17:31.080
Well, what happened
to that one?

17:31.120 --> 17:33.680
No, that was called
the Concept One.

17:33.720 --> 17:35.960
JEREMY: Mm-hm.
-And they only made
eight of those, actually.

17:36.000 --> 17:38.360
-Seven. Shut up!

17:38.400 --> 17:39.680
What happened
to the other one, Hammond?

17:39.720 --> 17:41.400
Just stop saying things!

17:41.440 --> 17:43.360
The new one is gonna be
called the Concept Two,

17:43.400 --> 17:46.200
and amazingly they're saying
it's gonna be even faster,

17:46.240 --> 17:47.680
and that was blindingly fast.

17:47.720 --> 17:49.760
I actually don't believe
that you can make a car go...

17:49.800 --> 17:51.160
Well, they say
it's gonna be faster,

17:51.200 --> 17:52.360
and it's a bit bigger inside.

17:52.400 --> 17:53.960
Which you did need, cos
that one was quite cramped.

17:54.000 --> 17:55.960
-You can fit in this one.
-I could fit in the last one.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.360
You'd be less like Spam,
though,

17:57.400 --> 17:59.080
if you rolled it
over and over and over.

17:59.120 --> 18:00.800
It should be more dangerous,
you're right.

18:00.840 --> 18:02.480
We've actually got a picture
of the new Concept Two.

18:02.520 --> 18:04.400
Here it is, Hammond.
You'll like this.

18:04.440 --> 18:06.920
RICHARD: Oh, God.

18:08.240 --> 18:10.000
Ooh, now,
there's a new McLaren, OK?

18:10.040 --> 18:11.520
I've got a picture
of it here.

18:11.560 --> 18:14.400
This is staggering. OK?
I've got some of the details.

18:14.440 --> 18:17.360
It's their new flagship,
kinda replaces the P1.

18:17.400 --> 18:22.240
Super hard-core.
789 horsepower mentalist
that thing.

18:22.280 --> 18:24.880
And they've called it...
And this is
a tremendous name, I think.

18:24.920 --> 18:26.920
-They've called it the Senna.
RICHARD: Ooh, cool.

18:26.960 --> 18:29.000
JEREMY: I mean,
that is a really cool name
for a car like that.

18:29.040 --> 18:31.120
I'm glad they didn't
call it the Mansell.

18:31.160 --> 18:33.640
-No, less cool.
-With its droning
engine note.

18:33.680 --> 18:36.480
And it would have
a stupid moustache
above its number place.

18:36.520 --> 18:39.560
And if it were a convertible,
a tweed roof.

18:40.720 --> 18:43.280
McLaren Hunt could work,
cos he was quite cool.

18:43.320 --> 18:44.920
A terrible thirst, though,
it would have.

18:44.960 --> 18:46.240
Yeah, a lot of smoke
coming out.

18:46.280 --> 18:49.680
Every now and again it would
try and mount another car.
But it'd be cool.

18:49.720 --> 18:51.840
On balance, I think Senna's
probably the best name

18:51.880 --> 18:53.200
they could have come up with.

18:53.240 --> 18:55.080
Right. Now, what else?
What more conversation
have we got?

18:55.120 --> 18:57.280
-I have some conversation.

18:57.320 --> 18:58.960
You know last week,
you were talking about

18:59.000 --> 19:00.440
how you ended up
following a pigeon?

19:00.480 --> 19:03.480
-How fast did you
reckon it was going?

19:03.520 --> 19:04.720
Thirty-five,
I think you said.

19:04.760 --> 19:06.480
The other day, I was going
down a country lane

19:06.520 --> 19:07.960
and I ended up following
a blackbird,

19:08.000 --> 19:10.920
and that only does 28.

19:10.960 --> 19:13.920
And that's interesting,
cos that means a blackbird,
in level flight,

19:13.960 --> 19:15.240
is slower than a pigeon.

19:15.280 --> 19:17.560
What is wrong with you two?

19:17.600 --> 19:18.880
Why are you following birds?

19:18.920 --> 19:20.920
Why not follow Russian spies
or straying husbands?

19:20.960 --> 19:22.920
No, listen, Hammond.
Pay attention.

19:22.960 --> 19:24.760
RICHARD: Oh, God.
-I did some research on this.

19:24.800 --> 19:26.760
You know
the top speed of a pigeon,

19:26.800 --> 19:28.600
if it really puts
its foot down, is 90,

19:28.640 --> 19:29.880
in level flight.

19:29.920 --> 19:32.400
-Ninety miles an hour!
That is amazing,

19:32.440 --> 19:34.880
cos you wouldn't think
a pigeon's wings
could shift enough air.

19:34.920 --> 19:37.480
-No, I wouldn't think
about it!
-No, no, stop!

19:37.520 --> 19:40.960
You say that: a hummingbird
can fly faster than a goose.

19:41.000 --> 19:42.880
JAMES: Can it?
-Even though it's like that.

19:42.920 --> 19:44.320
-Nobody cares!
-They do!

19:44.360 --> 19:46.640
Stop ranking birds!

19:46.680 --> 19:47.800
What?

19:47.840 --> 19:50.280
-R-r-r-ranking.

19:50.320 --> 19:54.360
Anyway, I think
that the top speed of birds
is a new hit show.

19:54.400 --> 19:55.600
And you and I can host it,

19:55.640 --> 19:59.280
and you'll end up as Buttons
in panto in Swindon.

19:59.320 --> 20:00.640
And then
you'll shoot yourself

20:00.680 --> 20:02.480
in a room
in a Premier Inn one night.

20:02.520 --> 20:04.680
-Yeah.
-There'll only be
one police car outside,

20:04.720 --> 20:06.160
and it'll be
a Vauxhall Astra.

20:06.200 --> 20:08.360
That's your future!

20:08.400 --> 20:11.080
Anyway, that is enough
Conversation Street this week,
so let's move it on.

20:11.120 --> 20:12.840
Thank you very much.

20:17.280 --> 20:19.080
Now...
Now, as I'm sure you know,

20:19.120 --> 20:23.000
trying to set a speed record
is very, very dangerous,

20:23.040 --> 20:25.520
and especially if you try
to do it on water.

20:25.560 --> 20:28.640
In fact, over the years,
and this is a true fact,

20:28.680 --> 20:30.520
85% of everyone

20:30.560 --> 20:33.760
who's tried to break
a speed record on water

20:33.800 --> 20:35.640
has been killed
in the process.

20:35.680 --> 20:37.840
-Eighty-five percent!
-Yeah.

20:37.880 --> 20:40.320
But that's not the sort
of figure that puts us off!

20:40.360 --> 20:44.560
Exactly. Because there was
a 15% chance of surviving it,

20:44.600 --> 20:48.560
we decided to try and break
the UK speed record

20:48.600 --> 20:50.600
for amphibious vehicles.

20:50.640 --> 20:52.760
Yeah, first, though,
we had to build a car

20:52.800 --> 20:55.600
that could be driven legally
on the road,

20:55.640 --> 20:58.240
but that would also go
very quickly on the water.

20:58.280 --> 21:00.160
Mm. And how hard can that be?

21:02.240 --> 21:03.600
JEREMY:
Since we were trying to break

21:03.640 --> 21:05.760
an amphibious
speed record,

21:05.800 --> 21:08.120
the obvious
starting point...was here.

21:09.920 --> 21:12.680
At Huddersfield
International Airport.

21:15.680 --> 21:18.600
Why are we at Huddersfield
International Airport?

21:18.640 --> 21:20.000
Yeah,
why aren't we at a lake?

21:20.040 --> 21:21.960
Because I'm project leader,

21:22.000 --> 21:24.600
and one of the many, many
things that I know

21:24.640 --> 21:27.120
is that to go fast on water,

21:27.160 --> 21:30.280
you have to have
a lot of power.

21:31.520 --> 21:34.080
To demonstrate
what I was on about,

21:34.120 --> 21:35.240
I'd set up a test,

21:35.280 --> 21:38.800
using the jet engine
from an RAF Nimrod.

21:43.760 --> 21:45.080
-Yes.

21:45.120 --> 21:46.760
JAMES: Can I just ask...
JEREMY: What?

21:46.800 --> 21:50.480
...what is the current
speed record
for amphibious vehicles?

21:50.520 --> 21:53.560
Thirty-nine point one
miles an hour.

21:53.600 --> 21:56.960
Well, isn't this
rather overkill?

21:57.000 --> 22:01.480
Listen, Usain Bolt can run
at 27mph on land, OK?

22:01.520 --> 22:03.320
If he were waist-deep
in water,

22:03.360 --> 22:05.120
he'd have a top speed
of about one.

22:05.160 --> 22:08.080
Water's really sticky,
you need loads of power.

22:08.120 --> 22:11.360
I've got a word in my head
for all this,
and it's "impractical".

22:11.400 --> 22:12.760
I've got a word,
it's "shut up".

22:12.800 --> 22:13.880
-All right.
-We're going.

22:16.160 --> 22:17.760
-Very.

22:17.800 --> 22:20.720
-That's fired up.

22:20.760 --> 22:22.720
That's gonna drive air
into the big engine.

22:22.760 --> 22:25.480
-We've gotta get those
in the green.

22:25.520 --> 22:27.480
I hate it
when you've got buttons.

22:27.520 --> 22:29.440
I can't hear anything.

22:29.480 --> 22:31.400
Ignitors on.

22:32.880 --> 22:35.240
I'm gonna give it
some thrust now.

22:46.880 --> 22:49.120
Gonna go up to 100% power.

23:33.080 --> 23:35.320
JAMES:
You are a witless dodo!

23:35.360 --> 23:37.080
RICHARD: Look at it!

23:41.040 --> 23:42.120
JEREMY: Ah!

23:42.160 --> 23:45.600
On the upside -
there is an upside here -

23:45.640 --> 23:48.520
if it's capable
of doing that,

23:48.560 --> 23:51.560
imagine how fast
we're gonna go on the lake.

23:51.600 --> 23:53.160
-You're a cretin.
-Yes. Yes, yes, yes.

23:53.200 --> 23:55.720
None of this is based
on any scientific reasoning
whatsoever.

23:55.760 --> 23:57.240
You say,
"It's got a lot of power."

23:57.280 --> 23:58.720
"How much thrust has it got?"
"A lot!"

23:58.760 --> 24:00.560
Look what it's done,
it's blown two aeroplanes over

24:00.600 --> 24:02.040
and given us
a massive bill...

24:02.080 --> 24:04.760
JEREMY: Having proved
to my sceptical colleagues

24:04.800 --> 24:06.640
that jet power
was the way forward,

24:06.680 --> 24:11.120
we moved
to our technology centre.

24:11.160 --> 24:14.680
Here, we would fuse together
this Russian jet...

24:16.040 --> 24:17.160
..this speedboat...

24:18.320 --> 24:20.000
..and this Suzuki Jimny,

24:20.040 --> 24:23.400
and we'd end up with the
fastest amphibious vehicle

24:23.440 --> 24:25.200
Britain had ever seen.

24:26.640 --> 24:29.280
-We have an old Suzuki car.
JEREMY: Yes.

24:29.320 --> 24:32.200
A small, old, plastic boat
and a jet engine.

24:32.240 --> 24:34.520
And you're suggesting that
somehow we unite them all

24:34.560 --> 24:36.960
into some sort of symphony
of success and glory?

24:37.000 --> 24:38.200
Yes.

24:38.240 --> 24:41.200
This is the stupidest thing
I've ever been involved with.

24:41.240 --> 24:43.560
JAMES: It's idiotic.

24:43.600 --> 24:46.520
JEREMY: Having convinced
my sceptical colleagues
once more

24:46.560 --> 24:50.160
that my plan was a good one,
we set to work.

24:56.280 --> 25:00.120
And soon, our amazing
creation was ready.

25:22.200 --> 25:23.880
Right, as you can see,
everyone,

25:23.920 --> 25:25.760
this is fully road legal.

25:25.800 --> 25:28.600
Lights, indicators,
number plate.

25:28.640 --> 25:30.560
And a massive jet engine
just behind us.

25:30.600 --> 25:31.720
JEREMY: Yes.

25:31.760 --> 25:33.800
RICHARD:
More of an issue, though,

25:33.840 --> 25:36.240
was the passenger's
seat layout.

25:36.280 --> 25:37.360
I've gotta change gear,

25:37.400 --> 25:39.400
and it's right where
your penis is.

25:39.440 --> 25:42.480
I never want your hand that
near my gentleman's sausage!

25:45.800 --> 25:47.640
RICHARD: What are these things
above our heads exactly?

25:47.680 --> 25:49.400
These are the
stabilisation tanks, yeah?

25:49.440 --> 25:52.160
When we go in the water,
you lower them down
and they keep us afloat.

25:52.200 --> 25:54.360
I've got that. I've got that
when we fitted them,

25:54.400 --> 25:55.800
but what
we're now discovering

25:55.840 --> 25:57.840
is they make us more stable
on water,

25:57.880 --> 25:59.760
but a lot less on land!

25:59.800 --> 26:01.560
JEREMY: James,
why are you being so quiet?

26:01.600 --> 26:03.200
JAMES: I'm waiting for it
to fall over.

26:03.240 --> 26:05.320
JAMES AND RICHARD: Whoa!

26:05.360 --> 26:09.400
Will you stop making
stupid, childish noises!

26:09.440 --> 26:12.280
I think we've done
an incredible job,

26:12.320 --> 26:15.600
and I think I've been
a remarkable project leader.

26:15.640 --> 26:18.600
Why has no-one
thought to do this before?

26:18.640 --> 26:20.480
It's so logical
when you look at it.

26:22.120 --> 26:24.400
The car bit of it's working,
but it was already a car.

26:24.440 --> 26:26.080
That's not much
of an achievement.

26:27.560 --> 26:29.280
I'm gonna do a brake test.

26:29.320 --> 26:31.120
Ah! Oh! Oh.

26:31.160 --> 26:32.360
-Wait.

26:32.400 --> 26:33.480
Is that that...

26:33.520 --> 26:34.680
-Ooh!
-Oh!

26:34.720 --> 26:35.840
Yeah.

26:38.120 --> 26:40.680
JEREMY: Eventually,
we arrived at the lake.

26:43.440 --> 26:46.400
For our first
high-speed test run.

26:47.840 --> 26:51.240
And immediately,
Hammond chickened out.

26:53.360 --> 26:55.040
Why aren't you wearing
a fire suit?

26:55.080 --> 26:58.320
Um, jet engines
just aren't my thing.

26:58.360 --> 27:00.240
I'm gonna watch this
from the bank.

27:00.280 --> 27:01.720
Are you really
not coming in it?

27:01.760 --> 27:04.280
No, I'm gonna watch--
I'm gonna be the observer.

27:04.320 --> 27:05.800
Oof!

27:13.040 --> 27:14.680
JEREMY: Oh. She's ready.

27:15.680 --> 27:18.080
My big fear is,
let's be modest

27:18.120 --> 27:20.560
and let's say we reached 80.

27:20.600 --> 27:24.360
So from here, we've got to
just use drag to slow us down

27:24.400 --> 27:25.600
before we hit the far bank.

27:25.640 --> 27:28.240
Well,
we have to think ahead, yes.

27:28.280 --> 27:31.000
Start decelerating
when you pass that mid-point,

27:31.040 --> 27:33.080
-you should be all right.
JAMES: I think he's right.

27:33.120 --> 27:34.480
The middle
is the critical point.

27:34.520 --> 27:36.160
RICHARD: Then just back off
the throttles.

27:36.200 --> 27:38.960
-And then we'll use the drag of
the pontoons to slow us down?
-Yeah.

27:39.000 --> 27:40.560
OK.

27:40.600 --> 27:42.920
Right.

27:42.960 --> 27:46.160
JEREMY: Soon, James and I
were ready for the test,

27:46.200 --> 27:48.000
and not at all nervous.

27:49.640 --> 27:53.880
When we fire up the jet,
this Perspex
that I put in here,

27:53.920 --> 27:55.680
I put it in.

27:55.720 --> 27:58.000
So what if that just goes?

27:58.040 --> 27:59.480
You shouldn't have said that.

27:59.520 --> 28:01.320
You know in Die Hard 2 ,

28:01.360 --> 28:04.360
when the enormous soldier
is sucked into the engine?

28:04.400 --> 28:06.120
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, that's like that.

28:06.160 --> 28:07.480
It will be like that,
won't it?

28:08.720 --> 28:10.560
JEREMY: Ready?

28:13.440 --> 28:14.520
We are going in.

28:18.120 --> 28:19.560
Oh, I feel buoyancy.

28:21.360 --> 28:23.320
I am proud
of my two colleagues.

28:23.360 --> 28:26.360
This is...this is historic.

28:26.400 --> 28:28.640
JEREMY: We are now
gonna fire up the jet engine.

28:28.680 --> 28:30.760
Right. Put your thing on,
it's gonna be bloody loud.

28:30.800 --> 28:31.880
-These things.

28:31.920 --> 28:33.240
That's a good point.

28:33.280 --> 28:35.840
-Right.
-Comms check, comms check.

28:35.880 --> 28:37.960
Dials are engaged.

28:38.000 --> 28:39.120
This is the speedometer.

28:39.160 --> 28:41.080
OK, we've got ignitor on,
bilge pump off,

28:41.120 --> 28:42.200
throttle set at idle.

28:42.240 --> 28:44.480
-Go.
-Starting jet.

28:47.000 --> 28:48.240
Holy shit!

28:49.440 --> 28:51.480
It's going...
Don't look at it!

28:51.520 --> 28:53.320
JEREMY: Don't look
in the rear-view mirror.

29:04.640 --> 29:06.280
Oh, this is phenomenal!

29:07.960 --> 29:10.080
Taking up the power now.
Fifty percent.

29:10.120 --> 29:11.640
Is that 50%?

29:11.680 --> 29:14.640
Yeah, that's about 50,
but 70 is 100.

29:14.680 --> 29:16.480
What do you mean,
"70 is 100"?

29:16.520 --> 29:19.560
I couldn't find a dial that
exactly matched the revs,

29:19.600 --> 29:23.200
so 70 on here is 100% thrust.

29:24.600 --> 29:26.480
JEREMY: I'm going full power.
Here we go.

29:28.440 --> 29:30.720
Hold tight. You wanna hold
on to something, seriously.

29:30.760 --> 29:32.080
Right, go.

29:36.080 --> 29:37.840
JEREMY: That's 100% thrust.

29:56.240 --> 29:57.960
Right, well,
we're doing 2mph.

29:58.000 --> 30:00.440
JEREMY: Come on!

30:00.480 --> 30:02.640
We're doing three!

30:02.680 --> 30:04.720
Why is it so slow?

30:04.760 --> 30:07.520
I mean, that jet
is from a Russian fighter!

30:07.560 --> 30:10.480
That is capable of keeping
a Russian fighter in the air.

30:10.520 --> 30:13.120
Why won't it make us
go more than three?

30:13.160 --> 30:17.160
In the air,
that's the point - the air!

30:19.000 --> 30:21.160
Hammond is keeping up
with us.

30:22.840 --> 30:23.960
That's it?

30:24.000 --> 30:26.920
Come on!

30:26.960 --> 30:29.360
-We're sinking.

30:29.400 --> 30:31.280
No, my half is sinking.

30:31.320 --> 30:34.680
Oh, God! We really do need...
I'm gonna go in to shore.

30:37.840 --> 30:40.560
I don't think they needed
the neck braces in the end.

30:46.000 --> 30:47.960
JAMES: And throttle back.

30:53.520 --> 30:54.920
-Three.

30:54.960 --> 30:57.440
RICHARD: Three?
-Yeah, it does three.

30:57.480 --> 30:59.080
That's your top speed,
it's three?

31:00.080 --> 31:02.720
You could row at 3mph.

31:03.880 --> 31:05.880
JEREMY: On the upside,
and there is one,

31:05.920 --> 31:08.280
neither of us were killed.

31:08.320 --> 31:09.680
And that's an upside?

31:09.720 --> 31:11.800
No, the issue at hand is...

31:11.840 --> 31:13.360
RICHARD: It doesn't work.
-Yes.

31:13.400 --> 31:15.080
Why doesn't it work?

31:15.120 --> 31:18.320
Well, it's mainly to do with
the shape of the car,

31:18.360 --> 31:20.800
the shape of the sawn-up bits
of tatty old boat

31:20.840 --> 31:22.360
that you've Blu-Tacked to it.

31:22.400 --> 31:23.960
The drag of the pontoons,

31:24.000 --> 31:26.400
the size and power
and position of the engine,

31:26.440 --> 31:27.880
the amount of fuel
it will run,

31:27.920 --> 31:29.240
the basic physics.

31:29.280 --> 31:32.240
The fact that water is
750 times as dense as air...

31:34.480 --> 31:38.400
JAMES: It was time to go back
to the drawing board.

31:38.440 --> 31:42.280
And this time, we gave Jeremy
a job he could actually do.

31:45.280 --> 31:47.760
Now, this is the car that
currently holds the record

31:47.800 --> 31:49.560
for amphibious vehicles.

31:49.600 --> 31:51.520
It's the Gibbs Humdinga,

31:51.560 --> 31:54.080
and, as you can see,
it is not an ancient Suzuki

31:54.120 --> 31:56.200
with an old Russian
jet engine on the back.

31:56.240 --> 31:59.080
No, it's a light, plastic car
with a hull,

31:59.120 --> 32:02.240
and, as you can see,
retractable wheels.

32:02.280 --> 32:04.840
Exactly. And that's why
we have chosen,

32:04.880 --> 32:08.360
as the basis for our project,
this.

32:14.600 --> 32:19.480
Which is a Reliant Robin
in a 1970s leisure suit.

32:19.520 --> 32:21.600
No, it is a Bond Bug:

32:21.640 --> 32:24.480
one of the coolest cars
from the '70s.

32:24.520 --> 32:28.080
And I can see why you chose
this particular one, Hammond.

32:28.120 --> 32:30.560
It's got your name on it.

32:30.600 --> 32:33.520
Shut up. The only reason these
things never really caught on

32:33.560 --> 32:36.640
was because nobody thought
of making them amphibious.

32:36.680 --> 32:38.000
Yes, but we have, you see.

32:38.040 --> 32:41.560
So we're gonna fit it
with retractable wheels,
same as the Gibbs,

32:41.600 --> 32:43.680
and we're gonna use the
engine from one of these.

32:43.720 --> 32:46.080
JEREMY: A jet engine.
-Yes. Sort of, but different.

32:46.120 --> 32:47.200
JEREMY: It's my idea.

32:47.240 --> 32:49.000
The jet engine
was not your idea.

32:49.040 --> 32:50.720
No, the jet engine
isn't my idea,

32:50.760 --> 32:52.440
but the idea of making
an amphibious car

32:52.480 --> 32:54.400
using a jet engine
was my idea.

32:54.440 --> 32:56.880
This is a water jet,
it's different.

32:56.920 --> 32:58.600
And anyway, this is genius,

32:58.640 --> 33:00.560
because you can rent
one of these

33:00.600 --> 33:02.040
from pretty much
any beach in the world,

33:02.080 --> 33:03.960
that will do 50mph
out of the box.

33:04.000 --> 33:06.000
-This one will do 67.
-It will. Exactly.

33:06.040 --> 33:07.160
