JEREMY:
No, it's still brown...

45:57.240 --> 46:00.680
No, that is a James May
cornering speed through
that one.

46:00.720 --> 46:02.480
Is the car putting
traction down all right?

46:02.520 --> 46:05.560
DYNAMO: No,
it was all over the place!

46:05.600 --> 46:06.920
JEREMY: No, that's nice.

46:06.960 --> 46:08.920
Yeah, splashing through
the last bit.

46:08.960 --> 46:10.440
Difficult Bit 2
as we call it.

46:10.480 --> 46:11.760
It's driving on water,
this is.

46:11.800 --> 46:14.080
JEREMY: It is, yeah.
It's almost Jesus-esque.

46:14.120 --> 46:16.800
And then now we get
back onto the tarmac.

46:16.840 --> 46:19.480
Ooh, I say, that was tonnes
of front-end grip there

46:19.520 --> 46:21.160
all of a sudden.

46:21.200 --> 46:22.760
And look at the way
the front's turning in.

46:22.800 --> 46:24.080
That's unbelievable!

46:24.120 --> 46:27.600
Now, we go onto the
really fast bit, ordinarily.

46:27.640 --> 46:30.040
Come on, then. Here we go.

46:30.080 --> 46:33.200
JEREMY: This is where
you lost it in the practice.

46:33.240 --> 46:34.680
But you haven't lost it
this time.

46:34.720 --> 46:37.480
That front is suddenly
sticking really well!

46:37.520 --> 46:39.760
Coming up to the last corner.

46:39.800 --> 46:43.120
And a little bit of
understeer through there,
but nicely tamed.

46:43.160 --> 46:45.360
And there we are,
across the line, everybody!

46:48.040 --> 46:50.520
Nicely done. Not easy.

46:50.560 --> 46:53.360
Not easy.

46:53.400 --> 46:57.240
Now then, after you'd had
a go, it was your turn.

46:57.280 --> 46:59.000
-Yes.

46:59.040 --> 47:02.160
I had a very good time, yeah.
And I had Teller as a
passenger, which was helpful.

47:02.200 --> 47:04.720
Oh, that would help!
Balance it out nicely.

47:04.760 --> 47:06.080
PENN: Sure.

47:06.120 --> 47:07.680
You also had a moment,
shall we say.

47:07.720 --> 47:09.360
I did. I did, yeah.

47:09.400 --> 47:10.840
Would anybody like to see
this moment?

47:10.880 --> 47:12.640
AUDIENCE: Yes!
-Let's have a look.

47:12.680 --> 47:14.600
This is quick
coming into the last corner.

47:14.640 --> 47:15.800
That's understeer.

47:15.840 --> 47:17.640
Oh, somebody's been off there
already,

47:17.680 --> 47:20.320
you can see the tyre marks,
but not as far you went.

47:20.360 --> 47:21.680
That is impressive.

47:21.720 --> 47:25.040
That's the furthest anybody's
been off that track,

47:25.080 --> 47:26.480
by a long way.

47:26.520 --> 47:29.360
You're definitely
winning that, so far.
Definitely.

47:29.400 --> 47:31.720
Furthest off the track,
I got that.

47:31.760 --> 47:34.200
-But then you got a lap
together, both of you.
-I did.

47:34.240 --> 47:36.360
Let's have a look
at this lap.

47:36.400 --> 47:39.600
Yeah, another nice,
tidy start.

47:39.640 --> 47:41.400
Roaring off
down to the first corner.

47:41.440 --> 47:43.920
So, we're going, Teller.
Can you feel that?

47:45.240 --> 47:46.960
JEREMY: It's not at all
scary in there.

47:48.080 --> 47:49.720
Right, that's tidily done
through there,

47:49.760 --> 47:51.120
keeping it really
on the island,

47:51.160 --> 47:53.360
unlike Dynamo,
who was a bit mad.

47:53.400 --> 47:55.000
And onto the gravel.

47:55.040 --> 47:56.400
Well, the mud.
Well, the slush.

47:56.440 --> 47:57.760
Whatever you wanna call it.

47:59.240 --> 48:00.560
Ahhh!

48:01.840 --> 48:03.160
PENN:
I'm going quickly there.

48:03.200 --> 48:04.520
JEREMY: Oh-hoo-hoo!

48:04.560 --> 48:06.640
-That was well held there.
PENN: Thank you.

48:06.680 --> 48:08.280
JEREMY: That's nice driving.

48:08.320 --> 48:11.200
I'm under control.
Shut up, Teller! I got it!

48:12.360 --> 48:13.680
JEREMY:
Is he putting you off?

48:13.720 --> 48:14.800
Now, this is...

48:14.840 --> 48:17.160
Sometimes, when it appears
to be slow, it's fast,

48:17.200 --> 48:20.560
and sometimes, when
it looks fast, it's slow.

48:20.600 --> 48:23.280
This is looking fast,
I'm gonna be honest,

48:23.320 --> 48:24.840
but there's a lot
of sideways action,

48:24.880 --> 48:27.280
which, of course,
isn't forward motion,

48:27.320 --> 48:30.080
-which is a problem.
-But it looks really good.

48:30.120 --> 48:32.480
JEREMY: It looks tremendous.
This is great television.

48:36.360 --> 48:38.480
And you can hear the bark
of the two-litre there

48:38.520 --> 48:39.720
as you hit the straight.

48:39.760 --> 48:41.120
-We're going!
-Ahh!

48:41.160 --> 48:43.280
-Now! Boom!
-Oh!

48:43.320 --> 48:45.480
JEREMY:
And coming up to the...

48:45.520 --> 48:47.880
This is the corner -
not this one,
but the next one,

48:47.920 --> 48:49.920
that caught you out
practising.

48:49.960 --> 48:52.160
Ooh, you're trying to get
a Scandi flick going there,

48:52.200 --> 48:53.520
but a bit too soon.

48:53.560 --> 48:54.640
Understeer again,

48:54.680 --> 48:56.240
but you've held it this time.

48:56.280 --> 48:58.320
And there we are, yeah,
across the line, everybody!

49:09.000 --> 49:10.680
Right, I have the times here.

49:10.720 --> 49:11.800
OK.

49:13.480 --> 49:15.560
We'll start with you, Dynamo.

49:15.600 --> 49:18.560
One thirty-nine point three.

49:18.600 --> 49:21.000
-That's all right
-That's really slow.

49:25.080 --> 49:27.480
But you've got
the snow symbol.

49:27.520 --> 49:30.640
So far, you're
the fastest person ever

49:30.680 --> 49:33.680
to go round our track
in the snow.

49:33.720 --> 49:36.600
But are you faster
than Penn and Teller?

49:36.640 --> 49:38.880
There's actually
excitement here, isn't there?

49:38.920 --> 49:40.600
DYNAMO: Yeah.
PENN: There's nervousness.

49:40.640 --> 49:42.120
You did it in one...

49:43.520 --> 49:44.640
..thirty...

49:46.880 --> 49:48.360
..three point eight.

49:52.640 --> 49:53.880
DYNAMO: Bad boy.

49:53.920 --> 49:58.240
Commiserations.
Commiserations.

49:58.280 --> 50:00.360
Congratulations, gentlemen.
Congratulations.

50:00.400 --> 50:02.800
That was fantastic!

50:02.840 --> 50:04.440
And thank you so much,
all of you,

50:04.480 --> 50:06.440
for coming along
and doing all this magic.

50:06.480 --> 50:08.520
But we must now say goodbye
to Dynamo

50:08.560 --> 50:12.080
and the world's fastest
magicians, Penn and Teller!

50:12.120 --> 50:14.800
-World's fastest magicians!

50:20.000 --> 50:23.800
Now, tonight,
we are attempting to break

50:23.840 --> 50:27.160
the British water speed
record for amphibious cars.

50:27.200 --> 50:29.760
Now, earlier on, Jeremy
had a go at making something,

50:29.800 --> 50:32.400
and his effort
was, frankly, terrible.

50:32.440 --> 50:33.720
JEREMY: No, it wasn't.
-It was.

50:33.760 --> 50:36.400
Yeah, so, Hammond and I
took control of the project,

50:36.440 --> 50:40.040
and what we decided to do
was take a 1970s
three-wheeler

50:40.080 --> 50:42.080
with a removable roof,
called a Bond Bug...

50:42.120 --> 50:43.200
Here's a picture of it.

50:43.240 --> 50:45.600
..and mate that
with a jet ski,

50:45.640 --> 50:49.200
to create something that we
had christened the Pond Bug.

50:49.240 --> 50:51.080
And then,
when it was finished,

50:51.120 --> 50:52.560
take it to the Lake District,

50:52.600 --> 50:56.680
and something called
Coniston Speed Week.

50:58.240 --> 51:00.880
JAMES: Over the decades,
many fearless daredevils

51:00.920 --> 51:04.240
have powered across this
five-mile stretch of water,

51:04.280 --> 51:06.920
in the pursuit
of new records.

51:12.080 --> 51:15.240
One was the legendary
Donald Campbell.

51:16.320 --> 51:18.720
Who was killed here in 1967,

51:18.760 --> 51:22.800
whilst trying to break
the 300mph barrier.

51:30.880 --> 51:34.560
Today, in Speed Week, that
spirit of adventure lives on,

51:34.600 --> 51:36.520
as people
from all over the world

51:36.560 --> 51:39.080
come to push their boats,
their engines,

51:39.120 --> 51:42.080
and themselves
to the absolute limit.

51:43.400 --> 51:45.240
This was speed heaven,

51:45.280 --> 51:48.880
and I felt sure
our fully road legal Pond Bug

51:48.920 --> 51:51.040
would blend in perfectly.

52:13.480 --> 52:14.560
Morning!

52:20.960 --> 52:22.560
Look at all this!

52:25.680 --> 52:29.760
Having parked up, I went off
to find Hammond and Clarkson,

52:29.800 --> 52:33.000
who reckoned he'd come up
with something better.

52:37.240 --> 52:38.560
JEREMY: Are you ready?

52:38.600 --> 52:40.600
You're gonna not
believe this.

52:40.640 --> 52:41.800
RICHARD: OK.

52:41.840 --> 52:44.520
JEREMY: Behold my genius!

52:46.040 --> 52:47.160
JAMES: Oh, hello!

52:50.200 --> 52:51.280
JEREMY: Oh, yeah!

52:51.320 --> 52:54.920
RICHARD: That is actually
quite surprising.

52:54.960 --> 52:57.760
JEREMY: So, the tracks drop
down when you're near land.

52:57.800 --> 52:59.960
JAMES: Oh, very clever!

53:01.320 --> 53:02.560
I mean, I'm sorry...

53:02.600 --> 53:04.240
I'm gonna stand back
a little bit.

53:04.280 --> 53:08.280
..have I, or have I not
created something brilliant?

53:08.320 --> 53:10.280
JAMES: No.
RICHARD: You didn't build it.

53:10.320 --> 53:12.120
And it's very cool,
but you can't use it.

53:12.160 --> 53:14.200
-Because it's not road legal!

53:14.240 --> 53:15.520
Well,
put a number plate on it.

53:15.560 --> 53:17.800
It's not an amphibious car,
it's a boat.

53:17.840 --> 53:19.480
That's a boat
with legs on it.

53:19.520 --> 53:21.760
It's not eligible
for what we're doing.

53:21.800 --> 53:24.000
BOTH: Ah!

53:30.960 --> 53:32.280
-Oh, yeah!

53:33.480 --> 53:34.880
Look at it!

53:34.920 --> 53:37.040
That is a quality job.

53:37.080 --> 53:38.840
Why are you pulling
that face?

53:38.880 --> 53:41.040
It's the stupidest thing
I've ever seen in my life.

53:41.080 --> 53:43.200
It's the coolest thing
that has ever been!

53:43.240 --> 53:45.240
-Look at it!

53:45.280 --> 53:47.400
-RICHARD: These are the doors.
-JAMES: Yes, undercarriage
doors.

53:47.440 --> 53:48.520
What doors?

53:48.560 --> 53:49.800
RICHARD: You retract
the undercarriage.

53:49.840 --> 53:51.840
The front wheel goes up,
then these doors shut,

53:51.880 --> 53:54.000
you've got a smooth hull.

53:54.040 --> 53:55.760
So those...
What do the back wheels do?

53:57.520 --> 53:58.680
What about the chine?

53:58.720 --> 54:00.480
What do you mean,
"What about the chine"?

54:00.520 --> 54:02.000
Look at the chine
at the back.

54:02.040 --> 54:04.800
This is to attempt
a water speed record.

54:04.840 --> 54:08.560
RICARD: I know!
JEREMY: This is what you need
for a high-speed run,

54:08.600 --> 54:10.800
a smooth, rounded chine.

54:10.840 --> 54:14.120
When this is up here,
it's sharp.

54:14.160 --> 54:16.760
So, as you're going along,
you catch that,

54:16.800 --> 54:18.480
and it's gonna go.

54:18.520 --> 54:21.640
JAMES: We had to make it fit
round the wheel, otherwise it
wouldn't work on the road.

54:21.680 --> 54:22.920
You could have made it round!

54:22.960 --> 54:25.880
That was a difficult
fabrication job. It was much
easier to do it like that.

54:25.920 --> 54:28.000
I'm sure it's easier, but
you've created a death trap!

54:29.600 --> 54:31.640
Weight. Keep the nose down.

54:31.680 --> 54:33.640
-JEREMY: I know what it's for.
-RICHARD: Well, there you go
then.

54:33.680 --> 54:36.360
Isn't this thing
just gonna porpoise?

54:36.400 --> 54:38.400
-We don't know.
-No. Probably.

54:38.440 --> 54:39.920
JEREMY:
Anyone who gets in that

54:39.960 --> 54:42.440
-is effectively
committing suicide.
JAMES: No, they're not!

54:42.480 --> 54:46.160
Anyone who gets in that
is gonna look the coolest
person here, that's fact one.

54:46.200 --> 54:48.440
Which one of
you two's driving it?

54:48.480 --> 54:49.800
Now, that's interesting,
because...

54:49.840 --> 54:52.040
We've had a think about that.
It's gotta be somebody

54:52.080 --> 54:53.840
with a speedboat,
powerboat racing licence.

54:53.880 --> 54:55.880
-JAMES: Yes. Have you
got one of those?
-I haven't got one.

54:55.920 --> 54:59.640
I haven't got one.
Do I know anybody
who does have one?

54:59.680 --> 55:00.960
Yes, I do have
a racing licence.

55:01.000 --> 55:03.440
-Well, there you go, then.
-And here is your racing boat.

55:03.480 --> 55:06.360
Look what
we've built for you.

55:06.400 --> 55:09.040
-I am not getting in that.
-Yes, you are.

55:09.080 --> 55:10.440
No, I'm not doing...

55:10.480 --> 55:12.640
-No!
JAMES: Well, you have to.

55:12.680 --> 55:15.800
-You have to.
-I am not.

55:15.840 --> 55:18.160
And with that,
back to the tent.

55:20.800 --> 55:22.920
-This is broken.
-No, line it up with the...

55:22.960 --> 55:24.520
It is broken,
otherwise it would...

55:24.560 --> 55:27.040
You've used a removable
steering wheel before.

55:27.080 --> 55:28.360
JAMES: Line up the...
There you go!

55:28.400 --> 55:30.600
I've mended it.

55:30.640 --> 55:32.760
JEREMY: Knowing
that 85% of people

55:32.800 --> 55:35.120
who attempt speed records
are killed,

55:35.160 --> 55:37.720
and that the boat had been
designed by imbeciles,

55:37.760 --> 55:42.280
I was fervently hoping
that it would, at least,
be easy to operate.

55:42.320 --> 55:45.280
However...

55:45.320 --> 55:48.640
You have to drive it
into the water first.
It's still in road mode.

55:48.680 --> 55:51.360
And you do that using this.
That just teases it in.

55:51.400 --> 55:53.160
A little push, a little push,
and it goes in.

55:53.200 --> 55:56.600
Once you're in the water, you
have to retract the wheels,

55:56.640 --> 55:59.960
and then you disengage
the fan and the clutch.

56:00.000 --> 56:01.920
Then you have to close
the nose wheel doors...

56:01.960 --> 56:04.080
If you push it down once,
you're in neutral.

56:04.120 --> 56:06.600
You'll still rotate round,
cos the jet's
still running...

56:06.640 --> 56:09.560
Push it up,
you'll see the current
will flow on the ammeter.

56:09.600 --> 56:10.920
When you get
a current surge...

56:10.960 --> 56:12.160
Jet thrust trim is here,

56:12.200 --> 56:13.800
and it will appear
on your screen here...

56:13.840 --> 56:15.280
Hold that, and that goes...

56:15.320 --> 56:17.520
This one,
you pull it fully back.

56:18.920 --> 56:22.720
If you knew, and you
obviously did know all along,

56:22.760 --> 56:24.400
that I was gonna be
driving this,

56:24.440 --> 56:26.280
why have you made this thing
so complicated?

56:26.320 --> 56:29.320
-That's not complicated.
-We've simplified it.

56:29.360 --> 56:31.200
These instruments
are from the jet ski.

56:31.240 --> 56:33.000
RICHARD: Comforting.

56:33.040 --> 56:34.800
Comforting.
When you're on holiday,

56:34.840 --> 56:36.160
you've looked at those
and thought,

56:36.200 --> 56:37.440
"I'm having a lovely time."

56:37.480 --> 56:39.400
That's what
you're doing today.
The water will be colder.

56:39.440 --> 56:42.640
-Why don't you take
the checklist with you?
-Because it will blow...

56:42.680 --> 56:45.040
-It tells you the things
you've got to do.
JAMES: It's so easy!

56:45.080 --> 56:46.760
We've spent hours on that!

56:46.800 --> 56:48.560
The thing to remember
is that it's...

56:48.600 --> 56:50.320
Thirty-nine miles an hour
is really fast.

56:50.360 --> 56:52.080
JAMES: It is quite fast.
-It is really fast.

56:52.120 --> 56:54.840
But if you do 40, then
you're a world record holder.

56:54.880 --> 56:57.480
-Step out of here...
JEREMY: Not world.
It's a British record.

56:57.520 --> 57:00.600
-What other sort of record
would you want?

57:05.080 --> 57:06.520
JEREMY:
To set a speed record,

57:06.560 --> 57:09.560
you have to drive past the
start line marker buoys.

57:12.320 --> 57:14.960
You're then timed
over a kilometre,

57:15.000 --> 57:16.640
after which,
you turn round...

57:18.000 --> 57:20.320
..and do exactly
the same thing

57:20.360 --> 57:22.040
in the opposite direction.

57:23.920 --> 57:28.120
Your result
is an average speed
taken from the two runs.

57:30.800 --> 57:33.960
It all sounded
very terrifying.

57:38.880 --> 57:41.240
Please sink like a stone.
Please sink!

57:41.280 --> 57:44.160
Sink! Sink!

57:45.240 --> 57:47.160
No, it isn't. Damn it!

57:47.200 --> 57:50.000
-It looks good.
-It looks brilliant!

57:50.040 --> 57:51.720
RICHARD :
We have every faith in you.

57:51.760 --> 57:53.360
-We don't have every faith.
-No.

57:53.400 --> 57:55.600
No faith.

57:55.640 --> 57:56.760
JAMES: Wheels!

57:56.800 --> 57:58.120
Wheels coming up.

58:01.400 --> 58:04.280
JEREMY: It was now time
for the checklist.

58:04.320 --> 58:06.680
What do I do with the clutch?
I've forgotten that.

58:06.720 --> 58:09.840
Doors.
Doors. Is that right?

58:09.880 --> 58:12.400
How do I get it out...
Wait a minute. Right, bilge.

58:12.440 --> 58:13.800
No, that's bilge,
that's not right.

58:13.840 --> 58:15.080
No, it's just...

58:15.120 --> 58:16.720
Oh, this is terrible!

58:16.760 --> 58:18.800
Hammond! May! You idiots!

58:18.840 --> 58:20.720
JAMES: Why is he just
going round and round?

58:20.760 --> 58:22.560
Is there a record
for going round and round?

58:22.600 --> 58:25.840
RICHARD: Don't know, but if
there is, it's in the bag.

58:25.880 --> 58:28.360
Right. I think we need
to go to a better viewing
position to see his run.

58:28.400 --> 58:30.200
Let's go over there.

58:30.240 --> 58:32.520
JEREMY: With the ridiculous
checklist completed,

58:32.560 --> 58:34.240
I had to get some speed up,

58:34.280 --> 58:37.240
so I could cross
the start line at full chat.

58:39.640 --> 58:41.320
Visor down.

58:44.800 --> 58:46.880
It's on the plain now.
We're on the plain.

58:48.280 --> 58:49.760
It's very spray-y.

58:49.800 --> 58:53.640
It's a badly-designed hull.

58:53.680 --> 58:56.320
JEREMY: But the hull
was the least of my problems.

58:56.360 --> 58:58.320
Jesus Christ! This steering!

59:02.760 --> 59:04.440
Oh...

59:04.480 --> 59:05.880
It's a  nightmare!

59:07.000 --> 59:08.160
I can't steer it!

59:08.200 --> 59:10.160
I literally cannot steer it!

59:11.280 --> 59:13.080
I think
he's experimenting with it.

59:13.120 --> 59:15.200
I think he's sort of testing.

59:15.240 --> 59:16.520
Oh, my God!

59:20.440 --> 59:22.560
JAMES: It looks pretty good.
RICHARD: It looks fabulous!

59:22.600 --> 59:24.040
I bet it handles
like a dream!

59:24.080 --> 59:25.480
Oh, come on!

59:25.520 --> 59:27.280
I'm gonna crash
into the bloody safety boat!

59:30.080 --> 59:33.760
-Look, he's making turns. Yes!
-That looks tremendous!

59:33.800 --> 59:36.400
JEREMY: Three times
I tried to get the Pond Bug

59:36.440 --> 59:38.400
pointing in the
right direction.

59:40.200 --> 59:42.520
Absolutely impossible!

59:42.560 --> 59:46.160
And then I thought, "Sod it,"
put my foot down,

59:46.200 --> 59:47.920
and went for it.

59:51.400 --> 59:53.160
Oh, Christ!

59:53.200 --> 59:57.560
It's only my skill
that is keeping this pointing
in a straight line.

1:00:00.840 --> 1:00:03.320
And, to make matters worse
for a man on a speed run,

1:00:03.360 --> 1:00:07.160
I had no idea
how fast I was going.

1:00:07.200 --> 1:00:10.720
I've got a GPS speedo,
but I can't read it,

1:00:10.760 --> 1:00:13.120
because there isn't any GPS.

1:00:16.400 --> 1:00:19.480
Why have they given me
such shoddy workmanship?

1:00:21.240 --> 1:00:22.360
Oh, heavens!

1:00:26.480 --> 1:00:27.560
Oh, Christ!

1:00:27.600 --> 1:00:30.520
That's the worst thing
I've ever done, ever.

1:00:30.560 --> 1:00:33.640
And now, I've gotta
turn round and do it again.

1:00:33.680 --> 1:00:36.160
I've gotta wait
for my own wash to die down.

1:00:36.200 --> 1:00:39.080
That's what did for Campbell.
He went back too quickly.

1:00:43.280 --> 1:00:44.480
Here we go.

1:00:49.480 --> 1:00:51.480
That is my foot
pinned to the floor!

1:00:54.680 --> 1:00:57.960
Jesus!
It's starting to chain lock!

1:00:59.600 --> 1:01:01.560
It's really bad.

1:01:03.680 --> 1:01:04.760
Ahhh!

1:01:05.920 --> 1:01:07.520
And then...

1:01:07.560 --> 1:01:08.800
Oh, my God!

1:01:08.840 --> 1:01:10.760
Oh, no,
we've got a power problem!

1:01:10.800 --> 1:01:12.440
I'm losing power!

1:01:14.320 --> 1:01:17.440
May and Hammond have built
a piece of shit here.

1:01:19.120 --> 1:01:22.280
It sounds
a little bit inconsistent.

1:01:22.320 --> 1:01:24.400
That's maybe him
feathering the throttle.

1:01:24.440 --> 1:01:27.160
He is possibly finessing it
to keep it on the plain.

1:01:28.920 --> 1:01:30.520
Oh, no! Come on!

1:01:38.920 --> 1:01:41.120
Jesus! A lot of smoke.

1:01:42.240 --> 1:01:43.800
Well, that was a disaster!

1:01:43.840 --> 1:01:47.120
I've got no GPS, so I don't
know how fast that was.

1:01:47.160 --> 1:01:50.120
And the engine
is cutting out all the time.

1:01:51.600 --> 1:01:54.360
Basically, it was time
for a stern word

1:01:54.400 --> 1:01:56.440
with the
engineering department.

1:01:57.720 --> 1:01:59.280
-Right, you two...
RICHARD: Yeah?

1:01:59.320 --> 1:02:00.560
Not only have you
built something

1:02:00.600 --> 1:02:02.120
-ugly and complicated...
-It's not...

1:02:02.160 --> 1:02:04.040
JEREMY: No,
it's rubbish and lethal.

1:02:04.080 --> 1:02:06.600
JEREMY: The worst thing
is the steering.

1:02:06.640 --> 1:02:08.880
You cannot get it going
in a straight line.

1:02:08.920 --> 1:02:10.400
The steering
is a horrible compromise,

1:02:10.440 --> 1:02:13.600
cos it's gotta work
the steering wheel
and steer the boat.

1:02:13.640 --> 1:02:15.440
"Horrible compromise"
is a way of describing it.

1:02:15.480 --> 1:02:17.400
"Lethal" is another way.

1:02:18.480 --> 1:02:20.040
-It looked great!
-Looked great out there.

1:02:20.080 --> 1:02:21.240
JAMES: Yeah.

1:02:21.280 --> 1:02:25.040
-I was doing about 4mph.
-RICHARD: Well, that's a start.

1:02:25.080 --> 1:02:27.120
JEREMY: Then, an official
came on the Tannoy

1:02:27.160 --> 1:02:29.080
to announce my result.

1:02:46.600 --> 1:02:48.720
-There you go!

1:02:48.760 --> 1:02:50.200
We did it!

1:02:50.240 --> 1:02:51.480
What do you mean "we" did it?

1:02:51.520 --> 1:02:52.760
Would you have swam it?

1:02:52.800 --> 1:02:54.880
-I did it!
-We did it!

1:02:57.160 --> 1:02:58.320
Thank you so much.

1:02:59.800 --> 1:03:00.920
Thank you, thank you.

1:03:03.360 --> 1:03:07.200
Thank you! Thank you all
for applauding me!

1:03:07.240 --> 1:03:09.840
No, wait, they're applauding
us as a team.

1:03:09.880 --> 1:03:12.080
Listen! I'm sorry
to go on about this,

1:03:12.120 --> 1:03:14.320
but Roger Bannister
was the first

1:03:14.360 --> 1:03:15.720
to break
the four-minute mile.

1:03:15.760 --> 1:03:17.440
Not the man
who made his shoes.

1:03:17.480 --> 1:03:20.600
Edmund Hillary was the first
to go up Everest.

1:03:20.640 --> 1:03:22.240
Not the man
who made his rucksack.

1:03:22.280 --> 1:03:23.560
-So, I was the first...

1:03:23.600 --> 1:03:24.960
I was the first to do that!

1:03:25.000 --> 1:03:27.280
I broke the record,
not you two!

1:03:27.320 --> 1:03:30.160
Yeah, the truth is,
to be honest, we failed.

1:03:30.200 --> 1:03:31.640
You didn't fail.

1:03:31.680 --> 1:03:33.240
I mean, if you'd spent less
time getting your hair cut

1:03:33.280 --> 1:03:36.960
and more time
working on the engine
so that it ran properly,

1:03:37.000 --> 1:03:40.360
I reckon that thing
would probably do 60 or 70.

1:03:40.400 --> 1:03:42.160
On flat water,
it definitely would.

1:03:42.200 --> 1:03:45.120
Yeah, but the thing is,
we gave it the square chines,

1:03:45.160 --> 1:03:47.640
that really terrible
steering,

1:03:47.680 --> 1:03:50.840
the fantastically complicated
knobs and buttons and things.

1:03:50.880 --> 1:03:55.120
Basically, we built a death
trap, and it didn't work.

1:03:56.640 --> 1:03:58.880
Well, so you're...
Let me get this straight.

1:03:58.920 --> 1:04:01.920
You were hoping I would
become one of the 85%

1:04:01.960 --> 1:04:03.640
who died
trying to break a record?

1:04:03.680 --> 1:04:06.200
BOTH: Yes.

1:04:06.240 --> 1:04:08.480
So we're now actively trying
to kill each other?

1:04:08.520 --> 1:04:10.840
Yes, and we can't even
do that properly!

1:04:10.880 --> 1:04:13.720
And on that
terrible disappointment,
it's time to end.

1:04:13.760 --> 1:04:14.960
Thank you so much
for watching.

1:04:15.000 --> 1:04:16.520
-Goodbye!
-Bye-bye.
